---
import Callout from '../components/Callout.astro';
import GeneratedDiagram from '../components/GeneratedDiagram.astro';
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import {
	applicationSubstrateDiagram,
	mllmComparisonDiagram,
	trainingLoopDiagram,
} from '../data/diagrams';

const title = 'TEPA: A Tri-Embedding Predictive Architecture';
const description =
	'A whitepaper draft for TEPA, a flexible condition-conditioned latent world model architecture.';
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
	<header class="hero">
		<div class="hero-inner">
			<p class="kicker">Whitepaper draft | May 22, 2026</p>
			<h1>TEPA</h1>
			<p class="subtitle">
				A Tri-Embedding Predictive Architecture for flexible, instruction-conditioned world
				modeling.
			</p>
			<p class="standfirst">
				TEPA predicts consequences in latent space. Its central design move is to keep
				context, condition, and target as distinct learned terms while allowing the condition
				to be structured, unstructured, multimodal, or mixed.
			</p>
		</div>
	</header>

	<main class="page">
		<nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
			<p>Contents</p>
			<a href="#abstract">Abstract</a>
			<a href="#thesis">Core thesis</a>
			<a href="#conditions">Conditions</a>
			<a href="#formulation">Formulation</a>
			<a href="#training">Training</a>
			<a href="#interface">Interface</a>
			<a href="#evaluation">Evaluation</a>
			<a href="#limitations">Limitations</a>
			<a href="#references">References</a>
		</nav>

		<article class="paper">
			<section id="abstract">
				<h2>Abstract</h2>
				<p>
					This whitepaper proposes TEPA, a Tri-Embedding Predictive Architecture for
					instruction-conditioned world modeling. TEPA extends JEPA-style latent prediction by
					introducing an explicit condition embedding alongside context and target embeddings.
					The condition may encode a natural-language instruction, structured action, query,
					objective, attention target, counterfactual intervention, prediction horizon,
					demonstration, tool trace, or multimodal prompt. The model predicts a target latent
					rather than directly producing text, pixels, or control outputs.
				</p>
				<p>
					The motivation is to separate latent consequence prediction from domain-constrained
					action spaces. LeJEPA provides a theory-grounded JEPA objective with SIGReg, while
					LeWorldModel demonstrates that a JEPA-style world model can learn next-embedding
					prediction from pixels when conditioned on environment-specific numeric actions.
					TEPA keeps the same basic prediction logic but generalizes the conditioning
					interface itself. The action vector becomes a broad condition representation that can
					carry language, structure, numeric controls, horizons, goals, and task objectives.
				</p>
				<p>
					The proposal is intentionally framed as a whitepaper architecture rather than a
					completed empirical result. Its claim is not that TEPA is already a general-purpose
					world model, but that condition-factorized latent prediction is a plausible route
					toward one. The key design principle is: predict consequences in latent space;
					decode, retrieve, probe, plan, or control only when needed.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="thesis">
				<h2>1. Core Thesis</h2>
				<Callout title="Core thesis" tone="thesis">
					<p>
						TEPA extends JEPA-style latent prediction from a context-target architecture to a
						tri-embedding architecture over context, condition, and target. By replacing fixed
						environment action vectors with an explicit condition encoder, TEPA aims to create a
						flexible latent world model whose predictive perspective can be shifted by both
						structured and unstructured inputs.
					</p>
				</Callout>
				<p>
					JEPA-style systems learn by predicting representations of targets from
					representations of context. This is attractive because the model need not reconstruct
					every low-level detail of the target; it can learn to preserve the structure needed
					for prediction, planning, and downstream use. In image and video settings, this can
					mean predicting masked regions or future latent states rather than raw pixels.
				</p>
				<p>
					World-model variants add a further need: prediction should depend on what is done,
					asked, attended to, changed, or sought. A robot action, a time horizon, a
					driving-risk question, a spreadsheet query, or a counterfactual intervention can all
					alter what target representation should be predicted.
				</p>
				<p>
					Humans do something similar. Perception is not detached from goals: what a person
					notices in a room changes when they are looking for a chair, checking for danger,
					remembering where they left keys, or planning a path through a crowd. TEPA treats
					the condition as the machine-learning analogue of that perspective shift.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="conditions">
				<h2>2. From Domain Actions to Flexible Conditions</h2>
				<p>
					The central design move is to replace a domain-specific action input with a broader
					condition input. In LeWorldModel, the predictor receives a latent state and an
					environment action, then predicts the next latent state. That is already an important
					architectural clue: the action is not merely another observation. It is the control
					variable that determines which future should be predicted.
				</p>
				<p>
					TEPA generalizes that control variable. The condition encoder is meant to support
					numeric motor commands, natural-language instructions, structured action records,
					analysis queries, attention objectives, counterfactual interventions, explicit
					horizons, demonstrations, and mixed prompts. In dynamic settings, the condition may
					describe a transition. In analytic settings, it may describe what should be extracted
					or preserved. In planning settings, it may describe candidate actions to roll
					forward.
				</p>
				<Callout title="No mandatory schema">
					<p>
						TEPA does not require a typed schema at the base-model boundary. A later distilled
						model may expose a stricter task-specific interface, but the base architecture is
						meant to learn from many condition surfaces: prose, JSON, tables, gestures,
						trajectories, tool traces, and demonstrations.
					</p>
				</Callout>
				<p>
					This is why condition is the preferred umbrella term. Transition is useful when
					discussing state change, but too narrow for queries such as "can this budget absorb
					a $500 car repair next month?" or "analyze this sentence according to Universal
					Dependencies." The predictor is the latent transition or task operator; the condition
					is the embedded signal that tells the predictor which operator behavior is needed.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="formulation">
				<h2>3. TEPA Formulation</h2>
				<GeneratedDiagram diagram={trainingLoopDiagram} />
				<p>
					Let <code>x</code> denote the observed context, <code>c</code> denote the condition,
					and <code>y_c</code> denote the true target under that condition. TEPA learns a
					context encoder <code>E_context</code>, a condition encoder
					<code>E_condition</code>, a target encoder <code>E_target</code>, and a predictor
					<code>P</code>. The predictor maps a context embedding and a condition embedding to
					a predicted target embedding.
				</p>
				<pre><code>z_context = E_context(x)
z_condition = E_condition(c)
z_hat_target = P(z_context, z_condition)
z_target = E_target(y_c)
L_pred = d(z_hat_target, z_target)</code></pre>
				<p>
					The target <code>y_c</code> may be a future observation, masked region, parsed
					structure, answer state, risk state, retrieved example, counterfactual outcome, or
					a richer conditioned outcome bundle. The condition <code>c</code> determines which
					target should be predicted. This makes TEPA a tri-embedding architecture: context,
					condition, and target are modeled as distinct latent terms rather than being collapsed
					into a single context representation.
				</p>
				<p>
					In the core formulation, the condition embedding feeds the predictor only. The target
					embedding is already the conditioned true target. If the condition is "collision risk
					in five seconds," then <code>y_c</code> is the corresponding collision-risk target. If
					the condition is "can this budget absorb a $500 car repair next month?" then
					<code>y_c</code> is the corresponding budget-stress target. No second loss-side
					condition term is required.
				</p>

				<h3>Shared Latent Outcome Space</h3>
				<p>
					The intended target space is a shared latent substrate across output types, not a
					separate handcrafted space for every task. In practice, this substrate may be a set of
					latent tokens, a hierarchy of embeddings, or a Matryoshka-style representation with
					coarse-to-fine prefixes. It should be universal enough to compare, retrieve, decode,
					probe, and roll forward outcomes, while still preserving the details that conditions
					make relevant.
				</p>
				<p>
					A single shared target space does not mean a single vague vector that must mean
					everything at once. The stronger claim is that there can be a shared outcome substrate
					that can represent many kinds of conditioned targets. The condition selects which true
					target is produced or constructed for a training example; it does not need to be passed
					again into the loss.
				</p>

				<h3>Coherence Hypothesis</h3>
				<p>
					The concrete hypothesis is that target latents become coherent when they are organized
					around outcome factors rather than output formats. Images, trajectories, parses,
					budget states, code impacts, and counterfactuals are different surfaces, but useful
					predictions often preserve recurring factors: entities, relations, quantities,
					temporal structure, constraints, uncertainty, evidence, and affordances. TEPA bets
					that these factors can share a representational substrate even when the downstream
					decoder or probe differs.
				</p>
				<p>
					This should be treated as an empirical claim, not an assumption. The first version of
					TEPA does not need to prove universal cross-domain alignment. It needs to show that a
					single target space can stay coherent as conditions vary within one grounded domain,
					then progressively earn broader sharing.
				</p>
				<ol>
					<li>
						<strong>Intra-domain coherence:</strong> train one target space in puck world across
						final positions, trajectory heatmaps, collision events, and uncertainty. Test whether
						shared latents support multiple probes without sacrificing prediction quality.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Condition-surface alignment:</strong> express the same intervention as text,
						structured records, arrows, and demonstrations. Test whether equivalent conditions
						produce nearby target latents and decoded outcomes.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Outcome-factor transfer:</strong> add new conditions that query different
						factors of the same rollout, such as contact risk, goal success, or time-to-contact.
						Test whether the existing target space supports new probes with limited additional
						supervision.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Cross-domain expansion:</strong> only after the above succeeds, introduce a
						second domain that shares abstract factors, such as trajectories, quantities,
						constraints, or uncertainty. Test whether shared dimensions improve transfer rather
						than blur domain-specific detail.
					</li>
				</ol>

				<h3>Conditioned Outcome Bundles</h3>
				<p>
					The conditioned target should often be richer than the direct answer. A useful world
					model should not only learn that the answer is "yes," "no," "9.4," or "high risk." It
					should preserve the supporting latent factors that make the answer useful for probes,
					decoders, retrievers, planners, and controllers.
				</p>
				<p>
					For a budget question about absorbing a $500 car repair, the target could preserve the
					primary answer, projected cash balance, due dates, committed expenses, discretionary
					categories, likely shortfall, alternative scenarios, confidence, and source cells. For
					a collision-risk condition, the target could preserve plausible trajectories, object
					identities, relative velocities, time-to-contact, uncertainty, risk contributors, and
					safe-action affordances.
				</p>
				<p>
					This does not require a mandatory external schema. The target can be a dense latent
					outcome representation. But the richness is not free: each recoverable facet needs
					training pressure from labels, simulators, mechanical extraction, contrastive
					structure, self-supervised prediction, downstream probe losses, or retrieval
					objectives.
				</p>

				<h3>Rich Outcome Datasets</h3>
				<p>
					Some datasets may store a rich full outcome <code>Y</code>, such as a future video,
					simulator rollout, tool trace, or complete table state, rather than a separate
					conditioned target for every possible condition. That does not make the conditioned
					target appear for free. TEPA still needs a target-construction mechanism:
				</p>
				<pre><code>y_c = T(Y, c)
z_target = E_target(y_c)</code></pre>
				<p>
					The function <code>T</code> may be mechanical indexing, masking, a simulator or
					oracle, a formula engine, an annotation pipeline, or an auxiliary learned extractor
					trained with its own supervision and anti-collapse constraints. Without such a
					mechanism, the math is underidentified: the model has no way to know which aspect of
					<code>Y</code> is the true target for <code>c</code>.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="mllm">
				<h2>4. Why This Is Not Just a Multimodal LLM</h2>
				<GeneratedDiagram diagram={mllmComparisonDiagram} />
				<p>
					A multimodal LLM can answer many of the same questions in language. The distinction
					is not capability in principle; it is objective and computational shape. LLMs
					natively produce token sequences. TEPA natively produces a predicted latent target
					that can be compared, retrieved, probed, rolled forward, or decoded.
				</p>
				<p>
					LLMs also show that models can learn to interpret both structured and unstructured
					context in the same prompt. TEPA borrows that intuition but moves the native output
					away from text and into latent consequence prediction. A practical system could use
					an LLM to parse intent and explain results, while TEPA evaluates consequences in a
					compact latent space.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="training">
				<h2>5. Training Without a Mandatory Typed Schema</h2>
				<p>
					The model is not forced to understand the world merely because the architecture has
					three embeddings. The pressure has to come from the data, objective, ablations, and
					curriculum. TEPA should fail if it ignores the condition, fail if it relies only on
					language priors, fail if it treats numeric distinctions as decoration, and fail if it
					predicts generic average targets.
				</p>
				<pre><code>L_total =
  d(P(E_context(x), E_condition(c)), E_target(y_c))
  + lambda * R(Z)</code></pre>
				<p>
					An early implementation could reuse a LeJEPA-style objective adapted to a conditioned
					predictor: prediction loss plus SIGReg or a related anti-collapse regularizer. A
					frozen target encoder can simplify early experiments, because collapse is less likely
					when the target representation is fixed. If training examples store full outcomes
					<code>Y</code> rather than conditioned targets, the target should first be constructed
					as <code>y_c = T(Y, c)</code>. A scalable version likely needs learned
					representations, regularization, uncertainty modeling, and careful target construction.
				</p>

				<h3>Condition Equivalence</h3>
				<p>
					The base model should learn that different condition surfaces can express the same
					latent intervention. A movement can be written in prose, represented as structured
					data, shown as an arrow, implied by a before/after pair, or demonstrated in a trace.
					Training should include matched families such as:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li>"move the dot left seven cells"</li>
					<li><code>&#123; action: "move", dx: -7, unit: "cell" &#125;</code></li>
					<li>an arrow gesture over the context</li>
					<li>a short demonstration trajectory</li>
					<li>"where will it be after this command?"</li>
				</ul>
				<p>
					The point is not to privilege the structured form. The point is to make the model
					learn that many representational forms can bind to the same underlying intervention.
				</p>

				<h3>Training Pressures</h3>
				<ul>
					<li>Same context, many different conditions, many different targets.</li>
					<li>Same condition meaning expressed in structured and unstructured forms.</li>
					<li>Tiny changes in magnitude, reference frame, horizon, or goal that alter the target.</li>
					<li>Impossible, underspecified, or contradictory conditions.</li>
					<li>Mechanical, oracle-derived, or separately supervised target construction when training from rich full outcomes.</li>
					<li>Cross-modal targets: image, state, text, measurement, retrieval neighbor, control outcome.</li>
					<li>Shuffled-condition negatives and condition-only or context-only baselines.</li>
					<li>Long-horizon rollouts where compounding error exposes weak dynamics.</li>
				</ul>
				<Callout title="Architectural risk" tone="risk">
					<p>
						A universal target space can become too soft unless the training curriculum makes
						distinct outcomes painfully real. TEPA needs grounded interventions, dense
						counterfactual pairs, multi-scale prediction, and evaluation tasks that reward world
						understanding rather than fluent condition paraphrase.
					</p>
				</Callout>
			</section>

			<section id="interface">
				<h2>6. Predicted Latents as an Application Interface</h2>
				<GeneratedDiagram diagram={applicationSubstrateDiagram} />
				<p>
					The predicted embedding is useful because it does not commit the system to one output
					format. A decoder can make the latent visible as an image, waveform, parse, or state.
					A probe can extract a quantity such as budget slack, phase, risk, or object position.
					A retriever can find real examples close to the predicted consequence. A planner can
					compare candidate predicted latents against a goal or risk latent.
				</p>
				<p>
					This makes TEPA similar to an embedding model with a steering wheel: the context tells
					the model what is present, and the condition tells it which consequence, aspect,
					horizon, or target relation should matter.
				</p>
				<table>
					<caption>Example condition surfaces and target emphases</caption>
					<thead>
						<tr>
							<th>Domain</th>
							<th>Context plus condition</th>
							<th>Target latent emphasis</th>
						</tr>
					</thead>
					<tbody>
						<tr>
							<td>Finance</td>
							<td>household budget plus "Can this absorb a $500 car repair next month?"</td>
							<td>Cash timing, committed bills, discretionary slack, shortfall risk, confidence.</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Linguistics</td>
							<td>sentence plus "Analyze under Universal Dependencies"</td>
							<td>Dependency arcs, grammatical relations, ambiguity.</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Driving</td>
							<td>camera feed plus "collision-relevant objects in 5 seconds; velocity 34 mph"</td>
							<td>Objects, trajectories, relative velocity, uncertainty.</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Robotics</td>
							<td>workcell video plus structured gripper command</td>
							<td>Future latent for grasp planning and candidate action comparison.</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Simulation</td>
							<td>physics state plus "add 5 degrees Celsius"</td>
							<td>Counterfactual latent after the intervention.</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Code</td>
							<td>repository state plus "change the auth API contract"</td>
							<td>Affected modules, tests, and integration risks.</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Science</td>
							<td>time series plus "predict 10 units ahead"</td>
							<td>Phase, dynamics, uncertainty, extrapolation quality.</td>
						</tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
			</section>

			<section id="evaluation">
				<h2>7. Primary Evaluation: Puck World</h2>
				<p>
					A credible first evaluation should be narrow, synthetic, and hard to fake. The goal
					is not to demonstrate generality immediately; it is to test the architectural premise
					that a separate condition path improves controllability, condition-form
					generalization, and multi-query reuse.
				</p>
				<p>
					The proposed first test is a top-down 2D puck world. The context is a rendered scene
					containing colored pucks, walls, obstacles, and optionally a goal zone. The condition
					describes an intervention or prediction horizon. The simulator produces the
					conditioned outcome bundle after the intervention.
				</p>
				<table>
					<caption>Puck-world evaluation setup</caption>
					<tbody>
						<tr>
							<th>Context</th>
							<td>Top-down image or state grid with pucks, walls, obstacles, and goals.</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<th>Condition surfaces</th>
							<td>
								Equivalent interventions expressed as prose, structured records, arrows drawn on
								the scene, or short demonstration traces.
							</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<th>Example condition</th>
							<td>
								"Push the blue puck up-left with medium force. Predict 40 frames ahead."
							</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<th>Conditioned target</th>
							<td>
								Final positions, trajectory heatmaps, collision events, goal/contact flags,
								time-to-contact, and uncertainty when noisy rollouts are sampled.
							</td>
						</tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
				<p>
					The key test is semantic invariance plus physical sensitivity. The same context plus
					semantically equivalent conditions should produce the same predicted outcome. The same
					context plus slightly different force, direction, object, or horizon conditions should
					produce different predicted outcomes.
				</p>
				<p>
					Evaluation should include latent error, decoded target error, retrieval rank of the
					true target, collision-event accuracy, final-position error, trajectory heatmap
					quality, condition ablations, paraphrase invariance, magnitude sensitivity, horizon
					generalization, and composition tests. The decisive baseline is a context-stuffed
					JEPA-style model that receives the condition bundled into the context.
				</p>
				<p>
					The current puck-world result is intentionally modest but informative. Across a
					fixed-data, fixed-target, three-seed comparison, a latent TEPA model, a
					context-memory TEPA variant, and a context-stuffed JEPA transformer baseline
					perform in the same broad range on the first JSON-only benchmark. The
					context-memory variant is currently the strongest and most stable overall, while
					the context-stuffed JEPA baseline remains a serious comparator and wins one counterfactual event
					metric. This does not support a categorical accuracy-superiority claim for TEPA. It
					sharpens the claim: TEPA should be judged on whether it preserves competitive
					prediction quality while improving modularity, condition-path diagnostics, and
					amortized inference when many counterfactual conditions are evaluated against the
					same context.
				</p>
				<p>Values are mean +/- standard deviation across seeds 17, 43, and 101. Bold values mark the current winner for each metric.</p>
				<table>
					<thead>
						<tr>
							<th>Metric</th>
							<th>Standard TEPA</th>
							<th>Context-Memory TEPA</th>
							<th>Context-Stuffed JEPA</th>
						</tr>
					</thead>
					<tbody>
