							<td>Prediction-to-target linear R2</td>
							<td>0.913299 +/- 0.002923</td>
							<td><strong>0.932091 +/- 0.001762</strong></td>
							<td>0.906237 +/- 0.044096</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Final-position probe R2</td>
							<td>0.948676 +/- 0.001893</td>
							<td><strong>0.958487 +/- 0.001430</strong></td>
							<td>0.935375 +/- 0.033108</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>Condition-parameter probe R2</td>
							<td>0.776008 +/- 0.008914</td>
							<td><strong>0.818038 +/- 0.017387</strong></td>
							<td>0.724755 +/- 0.050849</td>
						</tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
				<p>
					The amortized counterfactual benchmark remains the clearest runtime test: encode one
					scene once, evaluate many conditions, and compare total latency, memory, prediction
					quality, condition-shuffle degradation, and stability against a strong context-stuffed JEPA baseline
					that must reprocess the combined context-condition input for each query.
				</p>
				<p>
					The current result should be interpreted as parity plus amortization, with
					context-memory TEPA as the best current candidate rather than a settled winner. One
					important caveat is that the context-stuffed JEPA baseline trains a joint context-condition encoder
					end to end for this task, while the TEPA variants used pretrained frozen condition
					encoders. That may let the JEPA baseline learn a more purpose-built task interface.
					The next fairness ablation should compare frozen-condition TEPA, fine-tuned-condition
					TEPA, scratch-condition TEPA, and context-stuffed early interaction on the same fixed target
					space.
				</p>
				<p>
					The identifiability report follows the newer LeJEPA identifiability analysis: it asks
					whether target and predicted latents behave like useful world coordinates, not merely
					whether the decoder heads score well. For each run, the report measures latent
					Gaussianity, direct prediction-to-target alignment, orthogonal Procrustes alignment,
					and linear probes from <code>z_target</code> and <code>z_hat_target</code> to simulator
					state, condition parameters, final position, contact variables, and trajectory
					summaries.
				</p>
				<p>
					This parity result is still encouraging for the broader research direction. It suggests
					that conditioned latent prediction may be the more important idea than any single
					factorization choice. A context-stuffed JEPA transformer is a strong route when
					early cross-attention between world state and condition is valuable. TEPA is a strong
					route when reusable world embeddings, modular condition encoders, and many
					counterfactual queries over the same context matter. A third candidate,
					context-memory TEPA, caches the context as reusable patch tokens and lets the
					condition perform a cheap cross-attention readout. These should be viewed as
					different points in a design space for general-purpose prediction models, not as a
					simple winner-take-all comparison.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="prior-work">
				<h2>8. Relationship to Prior Work</h2>
				<p>
					LeJEPA is the closest source for the training objective: it provides the theory and
					practical recipe for pairing JEPA predictive loss with SIGReg, avoiding many
					heuristic self-supervised training devices. LeWorldModel is the closest world-model
					precedent: it applies that style of objective to pixels and environment-specific
					actions. TEPA borrows from both but changes the conditioning interface. Instead of a
					fixed numeric action vector, TEPA proposes a learned condition interface intended to
					support instructions, structured actions, unstructured prompts, queries, objectives,
					counterfactuals, and horizons.
				</p>
				<p>
					Klindt, LeCun, and Balestriero's follow-up identifiability analysis sharpens the
					reason SIGReg matters. In their setting, Gaussian latent regularization is not only a
					collapse-prevention device; under stationary additive-noise latent dynamics, it is
					part of the condition under which LeJEPA can recover world coordinates up to
					rotation. TEPA does not inherit that theorem automatically, because its target is
					conditioned and its condition interface may be text, structure, or goals. But the
					paper gives this work a better evaluation lens: target-space Gaussianity,
					linear-probe recoverability, and latent-space planning should be measured alongside
					endpoint prediction metrics.
				</p>
				<p>
					TEPA also relates to I-JEPA and V-JEPA as representation-prediction methods, V-JEPA
					2 as a bridge toward action-conditioned physical planning, and language-conditioned
					world-model work such as PAN and Dynalang. Its distinct emphasis is not video
					generation, language response, or a single control benchmark. It is explicit
					condition factorization as a route toward reusable latent consequence prediction.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section id="limitations">
				<h2>9. Limitations and Open Questions</h2>
				<p>
					The phrase general-purpose should be treated as an aspiration, not an achieved
					property. TEPA creates an architectural opening for broader conditioning, but
					generality would have to be earned through data, grounding, scale, evaluation, and
					downstream usefulness.
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li>
						<strong>Grounding:</strong> language can describe actions the model has never seen.
						The model only understands consequences grounded in trajectories, simulations, tool
						traces, supervised targets, or embodied interaction.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Numeric precision:</strong> text embeddings alone may not preserve quantities,
						units, reference frames, and compositional structure well enough for control.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Representation design:</strong> target embeddings must preserve
						condition-relevant details instead of washing them out through invariance.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Uncertainty:</strong> long-horizon predictions may need distributions,
						ensembles, diffusion-style latent samplers, or energy models rather than point
						embeddings.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Multi-resolution target embeddings:</strong> Matryoshka Representation
						Learning could make TEPA target latents usable at multiple prefix dimensions, enabling
						cheap coarse consequence prediction and higher-fidelity prediction when more
						dimensions are available.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>Evaluation:</strong> the separate condition path must outperform or clarify
						behavior relative to a monolithic context baseline.
					</li>
				</ul>
			</section>

			<section id="conclusion">
				<h2>10. Conclusion</h2>
				<p>
					TEPA reframes action-conditioned JEPA world modeling as condition-conditioned latent
					consequence prediction. JEPA decouples prediction from raw target reconstruction;
					LeWorldModel shows the utility of explicit action conditioning for latent dynamics;
					TEPA asks whether that conditioning interface can be generalized beyond a single
					domain's action space.
				</p>
				<p>
					If the condition encoder can learn to represent instructions, structured actions,
					queries, horizons, demonstrations, goals, and counterfactual interventions in a
					dynamics-relevant space, TEPA could become a reusable substrate for prediction,
					retrieval, planning, perception, and control. That is the ambitious path: not a claim
					that general-purpose world modeling has been solved, but a concrete architectural
					route for trying.
				</p>
			</section>

